Objective

By the end of this session you will be able to understand, What is meant by Immunity, the types of immunity, the terms: Adaptive Immunity, and Innate Immunity

What is Immunity?

Immunity is the ability of an organism to resist disease. This is achieved in the following ways. Activities of specialized blood cells, antibodies produced by specialized blood cells in response to natural exposure, injection of antiserum or transfer of antibodies from mother to baby via placenta.

Immunity prevents development of pathogenic microorganisms through the action of specific antibodies.

In short, Immunity is the quality or state of being immune

Types of immunity

Immunity can be either Adaptive Immunity or Innate Immunity.

Innate immunity

Innate immunity refers to nonspecific defense mechanisms that come into play immediately or within hours of an antigen's appearance in the body. These mechanisms include physical barriers such as skin, chemicals in the blood, and immune system cells that attack foreign cells in the body. The innate immune response is activated by chemical properties of the antigen

Adaptive immunity

Adaptive immunity is also known as acquired immunity or specific immunity. It is a subsystem of the overall immune system that is composed of highly specialized, systemic cells and processes that eliminate or prevent pathogen growth.

Adaptive immunity refers to antigen-specific immune response. The antigen must be processed and recognized first. Once an antigen has been recognized, the adaptive immune system creates an army of immune cells specifically designed to attack that antigen. Adaptive immunity also includes a "memory" that makes future responses against a specific antigen more efficient.

Immunity occurs as a result of prior exposure to infectious agents, prior exposure to antigens of an infectious agents, passive transfer of antibodies and immune lymphoid cells.
Adaptive Immunity can be Natural Or Artificial.

Artificial Immunity:

Artificial immunity is the way by which the body is given immunity to a disease by intentional exposure to small quantities of the disease. This is done by deliberate exposure to antigens, as in vaccinations or administration of antibodies.

Artificial Immunity can be Active or Passive .

• Active Immunity : Artificially acquired active immunity can be induced by a vaccine, a substance that contains the antigen. A vaccine stimulates a primary response against the antigen without causing symptoms of the disease.

• Passive immunity : Passive immunity is the transfer of active humoral immunity in the form of ready-made antibodies, from one individual to another. Passive immunity can occur naturally, when maternal antibodies are transferred to the foetus through the placenta. It can also be induced artificially, when high levels of human (or horse) antibodies specific for a pathogen or toxin are transferred to non-immune individuals.

For Example: administration of gamma globulins.

Natural Immunity:

Immunity that naturally exists, Natural immunity does not require prior sensitization to antigens. It is the normal resistance to infection.

This includes local barriers to infection- skin, stomach acid, mucous, cough reflex, enzymes in tears, saliva, skin oils which occurs as part of an individual’s natural biologic makeup.

In short,

It is the immunity that is present without prior immunization.

Natural immunity can be

• Active Immunity: Developed by own production of antibodies in response to an exposure to antigens, pathogens or vaccines

• Passive Immunity: Passively transferred from mother to foetus.
